Mesopodopsis slabberi : W. M. Tattersall 1922
, 1927 (partim: Port Said); Colosi 1929 ; Băcescu 1941 ; Ariani 1967 ; Daneliya 2002 ;
Kocataş et al. 2003
;
San Vicente 2010
;
Wittmann et al. 2014
.

In the Tamar River estuary at the E-Atlantic coast of SW-England,
M. slabberi
shows a less wide salinity distribution ( S > 5) compared with the co-occurring
N. integer
; there is differential distribution of age stages versus salinity, and the population shows a down-estuary movement in winter ( Moffat & Jones 1993 , Moffat 1996 ). In accordance with this,
M. slabberi
tends to disappear in winter when salinity decreases to values below S = 5 and water temperature below 10°C in a warm-temperate estuary at the coast of Portugal (
Azeiteiro et al. 1999
). Its abundance along the Westerschelde estuary at the Dutch-Belgian border is primarily correlated with temperature (
Rappé et al. 2011
), whereas primarily with salinity in the Guadalquivir (SW-Spain;
Fernández-Delgado et al. 2007
) and Gironde (W-France; Castel 1993 ,
David et al. 2005
) estuaries.
